#essentially looking to plot this onto the individual data plot

library(ggplot2)
ggplot(liver_sum1, aes(x = Genotype, y = Normalized.Signal))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = Normalized.Signal - sd,
                ymax = Normalized.Signal + sd))

#ggplot(heart) plots Normalized.Signal as a function of Genotype
#geom_point plots individual observations on this plot
#geom_errorbar points to my group means df heart_sum1 and the bounds of the mean+/- standard error bar
#the successive geom_point plots the mean; specify color so it does not conflict with the color call in the first geom_point

ggplot(liver,aes(x = Genotype,
                 y = Normalized.Signal))+
  geom_point(aes(color = Name,
                 shape = Replicate),
             alpha = 1.0)+
  geom_errorbar(data = liver_sum1,
                aes(ymin = Normalized.Signal-sd,
                    ymax = Normalized.Signal+sd,
                    width = 0.2))+
  geom_point(data = liver_sum1,
             size = 0.4,
             alpha = 1.0,
             color = "red")+
  xlab("Naa10 genotype")+
  ylab("NAA10 signal normalized to
       REVERT total protein stain")

#hypothesis testing ##unpaired t-test null hypothesis: there is no mean difference in NAA10 signal between Naa10 female genotypes

Alternative: there is a difference in NAA10 signal between Naa10 female genotypes

##Unpaired t-test of NAA10 signal grouped by Genotype
t.test(liver$Normalized.Signal~liver$Genotype,
       paired = F,
       var.equal = F)

##verify genotypes of 4942 and 4924 (may be flipped in source data)
t.test(liver_c57$Normalized.Signal~liver_c57$Genotype,
       paired = F,
       var.equal = F)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  liver_c57$Normalized.Signal by liver_c57$Genotype
## t = -1.6874, df = 9.1762, p-value = 0.1252
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group KO/WT and group WT/WT is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -31346.475   4516.984
## sample estimates:
## mean in group KO/WT mean in group WT/WT 
##            16334.36            29749.10

2-sample t-test indicates there is no significant difference in NAA10 signal between genotypes; however, the means are non-equal.

t.test(liver_c57$Normalized.Signal~liver_c57$Replicate,
       paired = T,
       var.equal = F)
## 
##  Paired t-test
## 
## data:  liver_c57$Normalized.Signal by liver_c57$Replicate
## t = -5.7446, df = 5, p-value = 0.002241
## alternative hypothesis: true mean difference is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -31980.97 -12207.46
## sample estimates:
## mean difference 
##       -22094.22

Paired t-test indicates there is a significant difference between biological replicates on replicate blots. First I will analyze based on Replicate. Paired t-test already indicates there are differences between replicates so I dont necessarily need to do post-hoc testing. However, I will use a Tukey-Kramer test.

If I include more variables in my model (Replicate, Genotype) that drive changes in Normalized.Signal, I can use post-hoc testing to specify which biological replicates differ.

For later reference: just re-run the samples again (ideally from new aliquots).

However, the samples for this dataset have been used up.
